So today was not a good day. I came downstairs before doing my yoga practice and overhead my parents talking about how badly students have done in their GCSEs and A-levels this year (the corona pandemic - yay!). I'm getting my results in less than a week and to know that I'm probably not going to do very well, or get the grades I was aiming for, was gut-wrenching. I started the video and for the first time in the five months I've been doing Yoga with Adriene, I burst into tears. Somehow, this video was the perfect one for me today, the one I needed to acknowledge my anger and disappointment, and let it go. I'm still sure I'm going to be upset on the day, but this practice gave me the tools I needed to cope better with my feelings. So I dedicate my practice to anyone out there who's feeling angry or sad or disappointed - I hope you find the peace you deserve. Thank you everyone - we're almost there! Keep going! xxx

Every day as I've been on this Dedicate journey, I've written down my own personal reflections after completing the practice. Today was my longest entry so far, and it's only fitting that it is the "Dedicate" practice. Adriene, thank you so much for all that you do with this community, you are truly inspiring and helping so many people. I never thought I could get into yoga a few months ago but here I am going through an entire - dare I say it - spiritual awakening. I really am on the path to righteous self-discovery and it is through your videos that I have been able to find the strength to do so. A little nervous to be commenting this as one of the major things I struggle with is other's opinions of me - so putting this out there for potentially anyone to see is scary. This community is so accepting, if you took the time to read this, thank you. 

Also wanted to add - my dog Bailee came up to check in on me as we did the pulses/breath of fire and it made my heart melt. Love seeing Benji interact and check in with Adriene too. Extending my love to you all! Namaste.

...i just did this practice after one restless night, as an American aboard, watching the news about everything happening there now with such... sorrow and sadness and confusion and anger.... but also so much love and community happening for those standing up for one another's humanness. showing up for one another and trying to be better. it was really hard to show up today. i'm fighting back tears as i right this now, but i realized how important it is to show up. because, when we show up, even in our pain and sorrow and hurt and disgust and confused energies, we come into our light and can refocus and shift our energy to something for the greater good. i dedicate my practice today to my country, the country I love so much. To people fighting and showing up for those being killed because the color of their skin. We can lose ourselves in the flood of emotion and become powerless to move in this density now... but we need still to fight that and show up. Be the light and work towards reclaiming and doing the work needed to heal. I dedicate this practice to Americans and my America. We will show up and heal and listen and learn and be better. Thank you Adriene for this timely practice.

Doing this a few days after the death of George Floyd in America. Dedicating this practice to all those who suffer at the hand of racism. Okay, time for constructive criticsm. 
I have done the challenge so far and I thank you for giving this opportunity. Yet, I have a few points that I feel hold this or would hold future series like this back: 
The last session was the first where I felt pace and difficulty were at a good balance before that everything was a bit too easy even for a total beginner. I think a slighty higher pace also makes it easier to go with the breath. 
Then the thing that I think is least helpful, is how much you talk. Don't get me wrong I like the instructions and I agree with a lot of the things you say about the more mindful parts of yoga. However, you talk probably 70% outside of the instructions, a lot of it repetitive and it sometimes seems you cannot stop yourself talking and let a mindful silence be. In future videos maybe trust your viewers to find that mindfulness themselves as you cannot talk it into them and when you try the opposite is achieved - frustration and the inability to connect to an inner calm because somebody is constantly talking. I hope this was not to harsh but I really feel that especially in yoga and mindfulness less is more.

Slowly it became a part of my morning routine.

Now it is meditating on waking, put on my Gamma & Beta binaural beat.

I don‚Äôt need a coffee now until long after seeing her place.

I dedicate today's practice to my family. As a hard working mom, who recently finished nursing school, I have always kept my workouts, prayer/bible reading, and meditation to a time when it would least impact my family, so that I could spend as much time with them as possible. This meant that I was doing these things while they were asleep or in school and don't see me in these activities. Doing Dedicate 30, I have been fitting practices in my day when they happen to be around, mostly because this has been a change of practice for me. Because of this, both my children and husband have begun to incorporate extra activity into their days. I didn't realize that I needed to model regular practice for them to understand the importance, but I will be doing more of this life-modeling in the future!! #Dedicate30 #changingthislife
